{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Renamed files appear in their own category and are not also counted as a deletion plus an addition.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real git rename detection plus CLI/report wiring. A unit test of classification logic can miss real failures caused by how git emits rename status and similarity thresholds. MOCK-HIDE: stubbing diff entries as already-typed records would hide parser/CLI mismatches. Rejection gate: Integration was considered, but behavior text explicitly targets repository-observed rename behavior, which depends on real git subprocess output, so Integration is disqualified.","test_description":"Create a real temporary git repo, commit a file, rename it, run the CLI against that repo, and assert stdout report shows exactly one rename and zero add/delete for that file.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.22,"System":0.7,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"Diffs that include binary files do not cause the tool to crash; binary files are counted in the output.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Crash risk is typically at real subprocess/output-decoding boundary (binary patch markers, encoding, command flags) and CLI execution path. In-process fakes usually provide clean text and miss decode/exit-code behavior. Rejection gate: Integration was considered, but behavior text explicitly requires robustness with real binary diffs in repository analysis; this depends on real git/OS interaction, so Integration is disqualified.","test_description":"Create a real git repo with a committed binary file change, run the CLI, assert process exits successfully and report includes the binary file in counts.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.04,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.82,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"Running the tool on a repository that has no commits yet produces an empty report rather than an error.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This behavior depends on real git behavior for unborn HEAD/no-commit repos (exit codes and stderr text) and CLI error handling. A mock can hide real command semantics. Rejection gate: Integration was considered, but the behavior text is specifically about a real repository state with no commits, which is governed by git subprocess behavior, disqualifying Integration.","test_description":"Initialize a real git repo with no commits, run the CLI, assert zero exit failure and stdout is an empty structured report.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.19,"System":0.75,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The counts in the report match the actual change history of the repository being analyzed.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"This is end-to-end correctness against actual repo history, requiring real commits, file operations, and git history traversal as used by the CLI. Mocking repo history can make counts trivially consistent with fixtures and miss real command/query mismatches. Rejection gate: Integration was considered, but behavior text requires matching the real repository’s actual history, which is a real infrastructure boundary.","test_description":"Build a real repo history with known adds/deletes/renames/modifications across commits, run the CLI for the target range, and assert reported category counts equal expected counts derived from git history ground truth.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.17,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The output is identical whether the changes being analyzed are staged or unstaged.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure appears at git index vs working-tree semantics and whichever